<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does wine cooler repair cost in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Our diagnostic fee is $120, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most wine cooler and bar refrigerator repairs run between $150 and $500. Thermostat, fan motor, door gasket, or thermoelectric module replacement is toward the lower end. Compressor or refrigerant work on compressor-based units runs higher. We provide a written estimate before any work begins. For units where repair cost approaches replacement cost, we'll tell you directly."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between thermoelectric and compressor wine coolers — does it affect repair?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, significantly. Thermoelectric wine coolers use a solid-state heat pump with no moving parts — they're quiet and vibration-free, which is important for wine storage. When they fail, the issue is almost always the thermoelectric module (Peltier element) or the control board. Compressor-based wine coolers use a standard refrigeration compressor and are more similar to a compact refrigerator — failures include compressor, refrigerant, fan motor, and thermostat. When you call, let us know which type you have or describe the unit, and we'll bring appropriate parts."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My bar refrigerator is not cooling — what are the most common causes?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "In order of likelihood: dirty condenser coils (LA's dusty environment clogs condensers faster than average), door gasket failure allowing warm air infiltration, thermostat drift, or refrigerant leak. For under-bar installations specifically — the most common installation in LA bars — condenser coil cleaning is the single most common fix. Condensers in enclosed under-bar spaces accumulate dust faster than freestanding units because airflow is restricted. Check that the condenser vent is not blocked before calling."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My kegerator is not keeping draft beer cold enough — can you repair it?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Kegerators are essentially undercounter refrigerators with a CO2 system and tap hardware. We repair the refrigeration side — compressor, thermostat, fan motor, door gasket, and refrigerant. The CO2 regulator, gas lines, and faucet hardware are typically operator-maintained; we'll assess on-site and advise if the temperature issue is in the refrigeration system or the dispensing system."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you repair Perlick, U-Line, Marvel, and True bar refrigerators?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Perlick, U-Line, and Marvel are the premium bar refrigerator brands most common in LA's high-end bar and hospitality market. True and Beverage-Air are the workhorses in commercial bar back-bar installations. We source parts through commercial refrigeration distributors for all of these brands. EPA 608 certified for all refrigerant work."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often should a bar refrigerator or wine cooler be serviced?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Every 6 months for under-bar units in active commercial bar environments — the under-bar installation accumulates dust and particulate on condenser coils faster than any other installation type. Annually for wine coolers in lighter-use environments. A service visit includes condenser cleaning, door gasket inspection, thermostat calibration, and fan condition check. For wine storage units specifically, thermostat calibration is critical — a 3°F drift in a wine cooler can affect long-term wine quality significantly."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

