<!-- THERMOELECTRIC VS COMPRESSOR -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02 — Two Different Systems, Two Different Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Thermoelectric wine coolers and compressor-based bar refrigerators fail differently — and need different repairs.</h2>
    <p class="lead">Knowing which type you have before you call helps us bring the right parts and cuts diagnostic time significantly.</p>

    <div class="compare-grid">
      <div class="compare-card">
        <div class="cc-badge badge-thermo">⚡ Thermoelectric</div>
        <h3>Solid-state cooling — no moving parts, no vibration</h3>
        <p>Thermoelectric coolers use a Peltier module — solid-state semiconductor heat pump — instead of a compressor. Quiet, vibration-free (critical for wine aging), but less powerful than compressor cooling. Common in standalone wine coolers and premium home wine refrigerators.</p>
        <p>Practical limit: thermoelectric units work best when ambient temperature is 60–80°F. In LA's warm garage or outdoor bar environments, they often struggle to reach target temperature.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Failed Peltier module — no cooling at all</li>
          <li>Thermostat / control board fault</li>
          <li>Fan motor failure — heat sink not clearing</li>
          <li>Ambient too warm for thermoelectric capacity</li>
          <li>Door gasket — warm air infiltration</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-card">
        <div class="cc-badge badge-comp">❄️ Compressor-Based</div>
        <h3>Full refrigeration system — more powerful, louder</h3>
        <p>Compressor-based units use a standard refrigeration cycle — compressor, condenser, evaporator. More powerful than thermoelectric; can reach lower temperatures and maintain them in warmer ambient environments. Used in all commercial back-bar coolers and most large wine refrigerators.</p>
        <p>The vibration from the compressor is why serious wine collectors often prefer thermoelectric — but for commercial bar use, compressor is standard.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Dirty condenser coils — most common</li>
          <li>Compressor failure or start relay</li>
          <li>Refrigerant leak</li>
          <li>Evaporator fan motor</li>
          <li>Thermostat or control board</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- UNIT TYPES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03 — Equipment Types We Service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Every bar and beverage refrigeration unit in Los Angeles</h2>

    <div class="type-grid">
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>Back-Bar Coolers</h3>
        <p>Upright glass-door refrigerators behind the bar — the most common commercial bar refrigerator in LA. Two- and three-door True, Beverage-Air, and Perlick units. Temperature-critical for proper beer service (38°F) and beverage display.</p>
        <div class="where">Bars · Restaurants · Hotel Bars · Clubs</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>Undercounter Bar Refrigerators</h3>
        <p>Compact units built into the bar — bottles, canned beverages, garnishes. Often Perlick or U-Line in higher-end installations. Enclosed under-bar space means condenser airflow is restricted — these units accumulate dust on condensers faster than any other installation.</p>
        <div class="where">Craft Cocktail Bars · Hotel Bars · WeHo Venues</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>Wine Coolers / Wine Refrigerators</h3>
        <p>Temperature-controlled wine storage — thermoelectric or compressor-based. Commercial wine coolers in restaurants and wine bars; residential and semi-commercial units in home cellars and Malibu/Beverly Hills estates. Precision matters: 55°F ±2°F for red, 45°F ±2°F for white.</p>
        <div class="where">Wine Bars · Restaurants · Residential · Estates</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>Kegerators</h3>
        <p>Draft beer refrigeration units with built-in CO2 system and tap hardware. We repair the refrigeration side — compressor, thermostat, fan motor, door gasket. CO2 regulator and faucet hardware is operator-maintained; we'll advise on-site which system is the issue.</p>
        <div class="where">Craft Beer Bars · Gastropubs · Taprooms · Restaurants</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>Dual-Zone Wine Coolers</h3>
        <p>Two-compartment units maintaining different temperatures simultaneously for reds and whites. Two independent cooling systems — both can fail independently. Common in wine bars and premium restaurant wine programs where both red and white must be served at proper temperature.</p>
        <div class="where">Wine Bars · Fine Dining · Hotel Wine Programs</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>Outdoor / Built-In Bar Refrigerators</h3>
        <p>Stainless-steel outdoor-rated undercounter units for LA's extensive outdoor entertaining culture — pool bars, patio dining, outdoor event spaces. Must handle LA's temperature extremes. Perlick, Marvel, and U-Line make outdoor-rated models common in Malibu and Beverly Hills properties.</p>
        <div class="where">Outdoor Bars · Pool Areas · Event Venues · Estates</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- WINE PRECISION BLOCK -->
    <div class="wine-block">
      <div class="w-label">🍷 Wine Storage Precision — Why Temperature Matters in LA</div>
      <h3>A 3°F thermostat drift in a wine cooler costs more than the repair</h3>
      <p>Proper wine storage requires 55°F (±2°F) for long-term cellaring, 45°F for white wine service, and 62°F for red wine service. A wine cooler thermostat that has drifted 3–5°F above target doesn't show obvious symptoms — the unit runs, the wine stays cool, nothing appears wrong. But wine stored at 60°F instead of 55°F ages 30–40% faster, and wine stored at 65°F+ experiences accelerated chemical degradation that's irreversible.</p>
      <p>In LA's wine bar and restaurant market — where a single bottle of cellar inventory can be worth $50–$500 — a miscalibrated wine cooler is a slow inventory loss that operators often don't catch until a guest comments on a wine that "seems off." We calibrate wine cooler thermostats against a certified probe on every service visit and document the pre- and post-repair temperatures.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04 — Common Failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians diagnose most often in LA bar and wine refrigeration</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Not Cooling / Too Warm</h3>
        <p>For compressor units: dirty condenser coils (the leading cause in LA's dusty environment, especially in enclosed under-bar installations), refrigerant leak, or compressor failure. For thermoelectric units: failed Peltier module, fan motor not clearing heat from the heat sink, or ambient temperature too warm for the unit's capacity. Check condenser coil airflow first — a blocked vent is the most common fixable cause before any parts replacement.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Temperature Inconsistent or Drifting</h3>
        <p>Thermostat calibration drift is the silent killer of wine storage units. The unit cools, cycles normally, and shows the set temperature — but actual internal temperature diverges from the setting over time. We verify actual temperature with a calibrated probe on every wine cooler service call. Thermostat replacement or recalibration is typically a $150–$250 repair.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Ice Forming Inside the Unit</h3>
        <p>Defrost system failure — the defrost timer or heater isn't clearing frost from the evaporator on schedule, and ice accumulates until airflow is blocked. Also possible: door gasket failure allowing humid air in continuously, accelerating frost accumulation. Ice buildup in a wine cooler can damage labels and affect humidity levels critical for cork integrity.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Noisy Operation</h3>
        <p>For compressor units: vibrating compressor mounts (common in older units), rattling evaporator fan bearing, or a loose panel in the airflow path. For wine coolers specifically, compressor vibration transmitted to the bottles is a concern — we check mounting and isolation on wine storage units. For thermoelectric units, fan noise is usually the only mechanical component that can cause noise.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Condensation Outside the Unit</h3>
        <p>Failed door gasket or anti-sweat heater on glass-door units allowing warm, humid LA air to contact the cold exterior surface. In coastal neighborhoods — Santa Monica, Venice, Malibu — marine layer humidity makes this more pronounced. Door gasket replacement is typically a same-day repair.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Kegerator Not Holding Temperature</h3>
        <p>Draft beer requires 38°F for proper serving temperature and to prevent over-foaming. A kegerator that can't hold temperature produces warm, foamy beer and forces the CO2 system to work harder. Most kegerator temperature failures are refrigeration issues — condenser, compressor, thermostat — not CO2 pressure problems. We diagnose both and distinguish them on-site.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

