    <p class="section-number">07 — Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">West Hollywood · Craft Cocktail Bar · Perlick 24-Inch Undercounter Refrigerator</div>
        <h3>"Undercounter fridge not cooling — everything behind the bar is warm"</h3>
        <p>Severely dirty condenser coils on a Perlick undercounter refrigerator installed in a tight under-bar cabinet with minimal ventilation clearance. The condenser — drawing air from an enclosed cabinet space — had accumulated enough dust and lint in 14 months of bar operation to reduce heat rejection to approximately 40% of design capacity. The compressor was running continuously but couldn't maintain temperature during the bar's peak service hours when ambient temperature around the unit climbed with body heat and lighting.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Deep-cleaned condenser coils and modified the under-bar cabinet to improve condenser airflow — cut a ventilation opening in the cabinet base to allow fresh air intake. Verified refrigerant charge (within spec). Compressor began cycling normally within 30 minutes of condenser cleaning. Temperature at 36°F within 2 hours. Discussed quarterly condenser cleaning for this installation — under-bar environments with restricted airflow need cleaning 2–3× more frequently than freestanding units. Bar back to full service same evening.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Pasadena · Wine Bar · U-Line 2275 Dual-Zone Wine Refrigerator</div>
        <h3>"White wine zone reading 52°F instead of 45°F — sommelier noticed oxidation"</h3>
        <p>Thermostat drift on the white wine zone of a U-Line dual-zone refrigerator at a Pasadena wine bar. The unit was displaying 45°F at the digital panel but actual measured temperature in the white wine zone was 52–54°F — a 7–9°F discrepancy caused by a failing temperature sensor. The sommelier had noticed that whites poured directly from the cooler felt warmer than they should and that one open bottle showed signs of premature oxidation. They had been running the set point lower and lower without resolving the issue, which is the classic presentation of sensor drift versus actual cooling failure.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Verified actual temperatures in both zones with a calibrated NIST-traceable probe — confirmed white zone 7°F above display reading, red zone accurate. Replaced temperature sensor in white wine zone. Recalibrated control board setpoints to match actual target temperatures. Verified both zones at target over 4-hour monitoring period. Documented pre/post temperatures for the bar's records. Discussed the sensor-vs-setpoint distinction with the sommelier — the instinct to lower the setpoint when the wine feels warm is correct symptom identification but wrong treatment when the sensor itself has drifted.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Malibu · Residential Estate · Perlick HP24WS Outdoor Wine Refrigerator</div>
        <h3>"Outdoor wine fridge not cooling — temperature climbing to 70°F+ on warm days"</h3>
        <p>Thermoelectric capacity failure on a Perlick outdoor thermoelectric wine refrigerator installed in an outdoor bar area in Malibu. Thermoelectric units have a fundamental physical limitation: they can only cool approximately 20–25°F below ambient temperature. On Malibu summer days when ambient reached 90°F+, the unit's thermoelectric module — even if functioning perfectly — physically could not achieve the 55°F target. The module was working; the installation was the problem. The estate had added outdoor landscaping lighting that directed heat toward the unit, raising its immediate ambient by an additional 8–10°F.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Tested thermoelectric module function — confirmed module output within spec. Identified the root cause as installation environment: landscaping lights 18 inches above the unit were radiating heat directly onto the top of the refrigerator. Advised repositioning the unit or switching to a compressor-based outdoor wine refrigerator for this installation — compressor units can achieve target temperature in ambient up to 110°F, thermoelectric units cannot. Client opted for a compressor-based Perlick unit. We assisted with the installation assessment and provided a referral to an appliance dealer. This is an honest diagnosis: sometimes the equipment isn't broken — the installation is wrong for the equipment.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Silver Lake · Craft Beer Bar · Kegco HBK309X-2 Kegerator (2-Tap)</div>
        <h3>"Draft beer serving warm and foamy — CO2 pressure already checked"</h3>
        <p>Failed thermostat on a Kegco 2-tap kegerator at a Silver Lake craft beer bar. The operator had already verified CO2 pressure and line resistance — correctly ruling out the most common causes of foamy beer — before calling us. The kegerator was holding 48–50°F instead of the target 38°F for draft service. At those temperatures, CO2 comes out of solution more rapidly, causing excessive foam regardless of line pressure settings. The thermostat had drifted from a calibration issue to an actual setpoint control failure.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Confirmed thermostat failure — thermostat was no longer cycling the compressor off at set temperature, allowing slow temperature drift upward. Replaced thermostat. Verified temperature at 37–39°F through 3 full compressor cycles. Also cleaned condenser coils while on-site — moderate dust accumulation contributing to the unit running warmer than it should. Explained to the bar manager the distinction between CO2-related foam (pressure, temperature, line issues) and temperature-related foam — temperature is always the first check when CO2 has been verified. Kegerator back to proper service within 2 hours.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
